10:57.090 --> 11:01.094 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
way? SETH BORENSTEIN: That's the
key question. Everyone says they

11:01.127 --> 11:04.397 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
want something binding, but it's
sort of, what do you mean by

11:04.430 --> 11:07.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
binding? And that's one of the
issues that's going to be hashed

11:07.033 --> 11:11.638 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
out here. It does involve lots
of new money, billions of

11:11.671 --> 11:16.276 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
dollars, if not eventually
trillions. It involves all these

11:16.309 --> 11:20.647 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
nations; 181 nations have made
pledges: Here's what we're going

11:20.680 --> 11:24.584 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to do individually. Now the
binding part is holding them to

11:24.617 --> 11:28.788 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
these pledges, a system to
monitor these pledges, and

11:28.821 --> 11:32.191 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
perhaps, if you're not reaching
these pledges, what do you do?

11:32.225 --> 11:35.695 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then it's all got to be
designed so that it doesn't go

11:35.728 --> 11:39.265 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
through the U.S. Senate, because
it can't go through the U.S.

11:39.299 --> 11:42.368 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Senate because of American
politics. GWEN IFILL: And

11:42.402 --> 11:45.004 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
American politics means that
that requires a two-thirds

11:45.038 --> 11:48.541 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ratification in the U.S. Senate,
and that's unlikely to happen. I

11:48.575 --> 11:52.045 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
want to ask Michael Levi about
what we have seen in the past.

11:52.078 --> 11:56.549 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have been to these meetings
before in Cancun and in Rio and

11:56.583 --> 11:59.786 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Kyoto and Copenhagen. Is this
one any different? MICHAEL LEVI,

11:59.819 --> 12:01.988 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Council on Foreign Relations: I
think this one is different. I

12:02.021 --> 12:05.224 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
think it's different because
we're starting to set realistic

12:05.258 --> 12:08.361 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
goals for what these summits can
accomplish. We used to go to

12:08.394 --> 12:12.465 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
these expecting to take a global
emissions cut that everyone

12:12.498 --> 12:15.501 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
needed to reach and negotiate
over how to divide it up, then

12:15.535 --> 12:18.071 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
everyone would go home and
execute that. It was kind of

12:18.104 --> 12:21.608 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
like old-style arms control
negotiations. I would get rid of

12:21.641 --> 12:23.610 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this many missiles. You would
get rid of that many. We would

12:23.643 --> 12:26.346 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
go home, we would do it. It
turns out that climate change

12:26.379 --> 12:29.415 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
isn't like that. Leaders can
agree to whatever they want, but

12:29.449 --> 12:32.785 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
actually changing the energy
economy is incredibly difficult.

12:32.819 --> 12:35.188 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it's a lot more like a
domestic policy problem, a

12:35.221 --> 12:38.591 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
domestic politics problem than
it is like a traditional foreign

12:38.625 --> 12:42.261 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
policy, national security issue.
So, what's different this time

12:42.295 --> 12:44.697 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is that, instead of putting the
burden on Paris to solve the

12:44.731 --> 12:47.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
problem, negotiators are asking,
how can we build an

12:47.734 --> 12:51.170 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
international agreement that
helps countries solve the

12:51.204 --> 12:54.574 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
problem themselves? How do we
help them cut their emissions

12:54.607 --> 12:57.210 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more deeply? How do we help them
adapt to climate change? I think

12:57.243 --> 12:59.212 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that makes this fundamentally
different. GWEN IFILL: Would you

12:59.245 --> 13:01.214 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
say -- Mr. Borenstein just
talked about the money which has

13:01.247 --> 13:03.216 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to be committed here. What would
you say would be the potential

13:03.249 --> 13:05.885 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
major sticking point in the next
11 days? MICHAEL LEVI: I think

13:05.918 --> 13:10.923 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the biggest sticking point is
likely to be over money. When we

13:13.159 --> 13:17.263 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
saw the clash in Copenhagen six
years ago, the ultimate turning

13:17.296 --> 13:20.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
point was over money. This is
money that comes from wealthier

13:20.833 --> 13:24.203 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
countries to help poorer
countries adapt to climate

13:24.237 --> 13:27.707 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
change, deal with the damages
caused by climate change, and

13:27.740 --> 13:30.043 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
transition their energy
economies. And it speaks to a

13:30.076 --> 13:33.112 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
basic political reality, which
is, if you're from a poor

13:33.146 --> 13:36.416 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
country and you go home from the
climate summit, and you say, we

13:36.449 --> 13:38.718 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have got some pledges, countries
are going to take action in the

13:38.751 --> 13:41.320 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
next 10 years, and that's going
to help us avoid dangerous

13:41.354 --> 13:44.223 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
climate change in the next 50,
your people are going to look at

13:44.257 --> 13:47.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you and say, what does that mean
to me today? If you come back

13:47.760 --> 13:51.431 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with pledges of aid, in
addition, then that's a stronger

13:51.464 --> 13:54.167 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
political proposition. If you
look at the basic politics of

13:54.200 --> 13:56.602 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
how this works, it leads you to
money. GWEN IFILL: Seth

13:56.636 --> 13:59.105 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Borenstein, we did hear,
speaking of money, today we

13:59.138 --> 14:03.743 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
heard private sector giants with
names like Gates and Bezos and

14:03.776 --> 14:07.747 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Zuckerberg promise to make a
commitment to a green energy

14:07.780 --> 14:11.584 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
fund. Does that change this in
any way? Or is this something

14:11.617 --> 14:16.255 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for the U.S. to trumpet? SETH
BORENSTEIN: This is something

14:16.289 --> 14:19.826 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
quite a bit different than in
previous years. You are seeing

14:19.859 --> 14:21.861 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- and this has happened in the
last couple of years, but it's

14:21.894 --> 14:26.365 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
especially happening now --
private industry money, business

14:26.399 --> 14:30.870 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is -- they're stepping up and
they're probably doing more than

14:30.903 --> 14:34.607 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
many countries, and that's
helping. They're seeing sort of

14:34.640 --> 14:38.878 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the reality of the economics and
climate change. And they're

14:38.911 --> 14:41.147 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
saying, if we're going to -- if
you're going to do something,

14:41.180 --> 14:45.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
let us volunteer, instead of you
impose, and let us help do

14:45.885 --> 14:49.288 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
something with technology. So, I
mean, what you're looking at is

14:49.322 --> 14:53.326 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
both technology and business are
dramatically different than,

14:53.359 --> 14:57.497 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
let's say, 1997 in Kyoto. Those
are two of the biggest reasons

14:57.530 --> 15:01.934 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
why many people are optimistic
this time, because the

15:01.968 --> 15:05.304 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
technology is so different, has
improved so much, and your --

15:05.338 --> 15:08.141 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and the business community, much
of the business community is on

15:08.174 --> 15:10.610 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
board now. GWEN IFILL: Michael
Levi, I want to ask you about

15:10.643 --> 15:14.380 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
two countries, not the U.S.,
involved in kind of whether this

15:14.413 --> 15:17.817 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
will succeed or not. One is
China and the other is India.

15:17.850 --> 15:22.188 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
How do you begin to take into
concern their concerns or their

15:22.221 --> 15:25.424 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
desire to make this happen or
stop it from happening? MICHAEL

15:25.458 --> 15:28.795 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LEVI: Well, I think the China
front, at least when it comes to

15:28.828 --> 15:32.465 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the diplomacy, is relatively
bright. The United States tried

15:32.498 --> 15:36.302 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
before the Copenhagen talks to
get on the same page with China,

15:36.335 --> 15:39.172 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but for the most part didn't
succeed, and the two countries

15:39.205 --> 15:42.275 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
clashed sharply at the
Copenhagen summit. This time

15:42.308 --> 15:45.411 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
around, they seem to be
considerably more successful.

15:45.444 --> 15:49.549 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They had an announcement last
year of mutual emissions-cutting

15:49.582 --> 15:53.586 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
targets. They had another this
year that put them on a similar

15:53.619 --> 15:59.258 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
page for the Paris summit.
Beijing is reacting to pressure

15:59.292 --> 16:03.529 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
at home to cut local pollution,
and the desire from Xi Jinping

16:03.563 --> 16:07.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to find an area where he can
work constructively with the

16:07.466 --> 16:10.970 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
world's biggest power in order
to build a more positive story

16:11.003 --> 16:14.373 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of great power relations in the
21st century. So, there, even

16:14.407 --> 16:17.176 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
though China has big challenges
in actually cutting emissions,

16:17.210 --> 16:20.213 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and so does the United States,
the two have been able to get on

16:20.246 --> 16:23.850 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a similar diplomatic pledge.
They will clash a bit in public,

16:23.883 --> 16:26.352 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but I think they have a script
in private. I think India is

16:26.385 --> 16:30.623 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
tougher. India is a far poorer
country than China. It is a

16:30.656 --> 16:34.193 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
country that is going through
enormous transition. It's

16:34.227 --> 16:37.530 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
impossible to predict what
Indian emissions or Indian

16:37.563 --> 16:40.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
energy use will be in 10 years
without policy, let alone to

16:40.933 --> 16:44.403 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
make promises about what will
happen to them with policy. And

16:44.437 --> 16:47.373 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
India also guards its
independence jealously. Even if

16:47.406 --> 16:50.576 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it thinks it can cut emissions,
it's very wary of signing up on

16:50.610 --> 16:53.179 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a deal to do that, a bit like a
lot of people in the United

16:53.212 --> 16:57.116 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
States. So, you will find India
is very sticky at these

16:57.149 --> 17:00.319 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
negotiations. It's tough often
to deal with. It won't promise

17:00.353 --> 17:03.823 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
all that much. But on the
ground, in practice, it's likely

17:03.856 --> 17:06.259 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to deliver considerably more.
GWEN IFILL: Seth Borenstein,

17:06.292 --> 17:08.861 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
briefly on that, to that same
point, especially on the India

17:08.895 --> 17:11.998 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
point. SETH BORENSTEIN: Well,
actually, I think you can't say

17:12.031 --> 17:15.301 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
enough about China. China is the
-- we will get back to India in

17:15.334 --> 17:18.170 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a second, but China is the major
player here. They're the number

17:18.204 --> 17:22.508 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
one carbon polluter by far. And
the difference between now and

17:22.541 --> 17:26.145 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Copenhagen is just night and
day. They are trying to be

17:26.178 --> 17:29.682 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
leaders in all sorts of things,
especially in solar technology.

17:29.715 --> 17:33.586 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So they are one the reasons why
there are so many people

17:33.619 --> 17:37.390 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
optimistic. India is the reason
why there are some people who

17:37.423 --> 17:41.427 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are still afraid things might
fall apart, because India is one

17:41.460 --> 17:44.530 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of these countries that still
wants to talk about the

17:44.563 --> 17:48.734 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
rich-poor divide. There are a
lot of poorer countries that

17:48.768 --> 17:52.905 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
continue the discussion of
developed vs. developing world,

17:52.939 --> 17:57.476 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and that helped cause problems
in Copenhagen. And they're

17:57.510 --> 18:01.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
worried that this might crop up
now. And we're hearing little

18:01.314 --> 18:03.849 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
glimmers of that here and there
now. GWEN IFILL: OK. Well, we

18:03.883 --> 18:06.485 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
will be watching all this very
closely... (CROSSTALK) GWEN

18:06.519 --> 18:09.422 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
IFILL: ... as I'm sure you will
too. Seth Borenstein of the

18:09.455 --> 18:12.858 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Associated Press and Michael
Levi of the Council on Foreign

18:12.892 --> 18:17.897 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Relations, thank you both.
MICHAEL LEVI: Thank you. SETH

18:20.833 --> 18:25.838 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BORENSTEIN: My pleasure. GWEN
IFILL: Tonight, we begin a

18:28.174 --> 18:32.311 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
week-long series on Africa's
most populous country, "Nigeria:

18:32.345 --> 18:35.948 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Pain and Promise." Special
correspondent Nick Schifrin and

18:35.982 --> 18:39.085 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
producer and cameraman Zach
Fannin spent more than a month

18:39.118 --> 18:42.088 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the ground there, chronicling
a nation in the midst of an

18:42.121 --> 18:45.925 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
encouraging and impressive
economic boom, but still plagued

18:45.958 --> 18:50.196 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by income inequality, corruption
and terrorism. This evening, we

18:50.229 --> 18:53.199 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
look at the government's
attempts to wipe out Boko Haram,

18:53.232 --> 18:57.269 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a terrorist group that killed
more people in 2014 than the

18:57.303 --> 19:00.539 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
